dismissalComment.html: goes for one too many and the top-edge lands into the hands of midwicket. The Zimbabwe fielders run up to shake his hands as Faf walks off the field. This was a touch quicker and not quite as short. Faf was just in that mode and has to perish. Standing ovation from the dressing room

dismissalText.commentary: Jean-Paul Duminy c & b Madziva 51 (62b 3x4 0x6 73m) SR: 82.25

dismissalComment.html: that's the slower ball, and it's fetched a simple wicket. Well done, Madziva. Gets a pat on his head from Faf as he walks off. This was a fullish delivery and Duminy, because of his attacking intent, lunges for it and goes for a swipe. Would have been served better hitting through the line. Ends up a top edge, and the bowler calls for it. Taylor backs off and the catch is taken

mid-off dives, he stretches out both hands to his right and takes it! Captain comes to the party and South Africa's openers are back in the hut. It was a fuller ball on off stump, Amla had crunched one of those to the boundary in the last over, but this time he has chipped it to Chigumbura! Bat turned in his hands, it hit quite low, and his usual timing deserts him again

dismissalComment.html: lots of flitting around the crease and he ends up nicking to the keeper. He made room first, then overcompensated by moving outside off. Phangiso didn't bother about him as he flighted one just outside off stump, the batsman goes for an airy drive and the turn elicits the outside edge. De Kock makes a smart grab and he knows it

dismissalComment.html: oopsy! He's sought a third run that his partner was absolutely uninterested in. Poor result for him considering he had nailed the sweep to deep square leg. Did everything right - rolled his wrists, kept it along the ground and nearly hit the gap - except look up in time to see Taylor's rather late call of no. Slips and has no chance of returning to safety

commentPostTextItems.html: So a rather straight forward finish which leaves us with a South Africa-Australia clash on Saturday. But for now, this is Alagappan Muthu saying sayonara on behalf of Vishal Dikshit and the scorers

Faf du Plessis is the Man of the Match "Just fortunate its coming my way, got dropped when AB got run out. Bit a a purple patch and I want to cash in. Thought JP played really well today, the pitch was really tough and definitely much harder than agianst Australia. His intensity helped me sit back and it helps us looking forward ot Australia. From a bowling point of view, I can give a lot of information about what Australia do. They only got one spinner with a few part-timers and spin would play a big part in the final"

"Losing a bit of control [with the ball]," AB de Villiers says. "Was a little kid with the ball, saw an opportunity to bowl. The bowlers set the trend up, I thought they were out of the game after 20 overs. Well played by Brendan though. I wont say its a problem [on turning pitches[, it is something we're working on. But we had enough firepower to look after teh game today and then in the next. We have to perform better in all three departments. Fafi was there at the end, we want on of the top guys to be there at the end and then the bowlers were very good, not always easy to get going when the game was going your way that much"

"It was a different wicket, a lot drier and was easy to bat on. In the afternoon it became diffuclt for us with their changes of pace. it wasn't too much, not really. The guys batted themselves in but gave wickets away cheaply," Elton Chigumbura says. "There's a lot to take from the series, the bowlers bowled great, but we have to put in performances together as a group"

4.55 pm ZImbabwe posed a threat, but not enough to pip South Africa's place in the final, not eventually was it enough to take the game. Brendan Taylor did his best to ensure the game was competitive but the difference between the two teams was a bit too much. Aaron Phangiso got the ball to turn and his accuracy was quite appreciable. But this victory was made by Faf du Plessis who compiled a third century in the series

"Nice to get a few runs. We were always behind the eight-ball losing too many wickets. but credit to Faf for his form. 272 on that pitch, which was breaking was difficult. He paced his innings brilliantly during that that partnership with Duminy. we thought 230-240 might have given us a chance, "says Brendan Taylor, "Just having Australia, South Africa has been special. Engaging against the best, you can only improve"
DanielAlexander: "JP bowled well today, don't think Tahir will play the final " Three wickets and his accuracy do make him a better package

commentTextItems.html: flighted on leg stump, whipped away through midwicket. They see the opportunity for a couple and commit fully to it. Chatara dives headlong to make his ground at the non-strikers' end
back of a length and outside off, eased away towards third man
that was close! AB knows it as he has hands on his head. Another offcutter pushed fuller and lured Chatara on a slog sweep, misses and it wasn;t too far away from off stump
another wide down the pads, found the block hole reasonably well though
seems to skid off the deck as Chatara blocks a shortish ball on middle
full on leg stump, Chatara tries to whip it away to square leg but misses.
that was the offcutter, gripped in the pitch and almost had the batsman out leg before. Instead its been flicked away towards midwicket
shortish and outside off, chopped away to point

commentPreTextItems.html: Warren: "Great stuff from Taylor here. Proving that he is good enough to play in a higher ranked team. Zim will probably fall short, but thanks to him, they will end up posting a respectable total. Pity that it took him 6 ODI's to do so...." Oh hello, here's AB again

commentTextItems.html: full and sliding down leg, as he did when he began his first spell
good length ball on off stump, Nyumbu tucks it through short leg and gets a single
pushed through outside off, Nyumbu shuffles across and blocks
flighted on middle and off, he blocks with some authority

commentTextItems.html: fired through outside off, with a round-arm action. Taylor advances and blocks
gets back over the wicket to the tailender and bowls a short ball, Chatara sways away and loses balance.
back of a length and outside off, steps away and thumps through to the sweeper

commentPreTextItems.html: Shalabh: "@Justin, but you also have to look that out of those 892 games how many are against the quality side? the problem is they don't get a chance to play against quality players.."

commentTextItems.html: gets down and slams a shortish ball through extra cover. That was just sheer power from Taylor, ugly swat to great effect
good length ball on off stump, Chatara defends with soft ahnds and it lobs away to the right of Amla at slip

dismissalText.commentary: Sean Williams c Amla b Duminy 3 (14b 0x4 0x6 15m) SR: 21.42

dismissalComment.html: thuds his bat into the turf as he walks away! Does not enjoy his walk back to the pavilion after the ball takes the inside edge, lobs off the pad and into Amla's hands at first slip. That's another delivery that went straight on, with the batsman playing for turn

dismissalText.commentary: Elton Chigumbura c Miller b Rossouw 13 (32b 0x4 0x6 32m) SR: 40.62

dismissalComment.html: that's short, it's been pulled... right into the hands of deep midwicket. First ODI wicket for Rossouw and he's chuffed, considering the ball he bowled. Chigumbura though was livid, slammed the bat into the turf

dismissalText.commentary: Malcolm Waller c de Kock b Phangiso 17 (22b 2x4 0x6 32m) SR: 77.27

dismissalComment.html: lots of flitting around the crease and he ends up nicking to the keeper. He made room first, then overcompensated by moving outside off. Phangiso didn't bother about him as he flighted one just outside off stump, the batsman goes for an airy drive and the turn elicits the outside edge. De Kock makes a smart grab and he knows it

dismissalText.commentary: Prosper Utseya c Amla b Steyn 0 (3b 0x4 0x6 6m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: that's a terrific catch from the mighty Hash! Diving low to his right at first slip. This was on a good length, hurried Utseya who pokes with his bat first and then the front foot follows. Amla had his eyes on the ball all through and just about managed to hold on

dismissalText.commentary: Neville Madziva run out (Miller/de Kock) 3 (11b 0x4 0x6 10m) SR: 27.27

dismissalComment.html: oopsy! He's sought a third run that his partner was absolutely uninterested in. Poor result for him considering he had nailed the sweep to deep square leg. Did everything right - rolled his wrists, kept it along the ground and nearly hit the gap - except look up in time to see Taylor's rather late call of no. Slips and has no chance of returning to safety

dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor b Duminy 79 (96b 5x4 2x6 156m) SR: 82.29

dismissalComment.html: goes for the slog again, the equation calls for it. this time though it was an awful hoick at the cost of his balance. Didn't get anywhere close to the ball and off stump is knocked back. Mangongo and the dressing room applauds

dismissalText.commentary: John Nyumbu lbw b Duminy 4 (7b 0x4 0x6 9m) SR: 57.14

dismissalComment.html: flighted on middle, Nyumbu goes for an across-the-line sweep. Hit in front of middle, Umpire Dar reckons it will go on to hit middle and that's all she wrote
